<seg id=1> Majority of Hong Kong People Reluctant to Call Themselves Chinese </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Hongkong AFP) According to an poll publicized yesterday, although Hong Kong returned to China last year, most Hongkongese were reluctant to call themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The result of the investigation indicated that, among all 6.5 million Hongkong residents, 40% of Hong Kong's residents call themselves "Hongkongnese", 22.3% call themselves "Hong Kong Chinese", and 20.6% call themselves "Chinese residing in Hong Kong." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> It was Society Science Research Center, Hongkong University that took this poll. </seg>
<seg id=5> Among the 517 polled, only 20.6% were willing to call themselves Chinese, and 1.6% didn't give a definitive answer definitely, nor did they express any opinion on the issue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In a similar poll made about half a year after the return of Hong Kong to China, 35.9% called themselves "Hongkongnese", and 18% called themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> It has been 15 months since the return of Hong Kong, and Hong Kong's government is always reminding its residents that they are Chinese. </seg>
<seg id=8> Hong Kong officers reprehended that the colonial system of rule present for the past 150 years has made many Hong Kong residents perplexed by the problem of identity. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Dong Jianhua, the Chief Excutive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, said that "I feel honored to be a Chinese person, and feel very proud of our nation's development," when giving a National Day speech, just 2 days ago. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> To invoke an enhanced sense of Chinese citizenship among Hong Kong's residents, The Hong Kong Citizen Education Foundation compiled and published a book, comprised of both pictures and articles, entitled "I am Chinese." </seg>
</p>
